WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:05.290
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:23.040 --> 00:00:24.340
&gt;&gt; Talia Guzman-Gonzalez:
Good afternoon, everyone,

00:00:24.340 --> 00:00:25.820
and thank you for being here.

00:00:25.820 --> 00:00:28.930
On behalf of the chief
of the Hispanic division,

00:00:28.930 --> 00:00:31.020
Dr. Georgette Dorn, I would
like to welcome you all

00:00:31.020 --> 00:00:34.310
to this very special event
with saxophonist, composer

00:00:34.310 --> 00:00:37.040
and educator, Miguel Zenon.

00:00:37.040 --> 00:00:40.290
I am joined by my colleague from
the music division Larry Applebaum

00:00:40.290 --> 00:00:44.510
who is senior music reference
specialist in the music division.

00:00:44.510 --> 00:00:47.980
I am Talia Guzman-Gonzalez
and I am a reference librarian

00:00:47.980 --> 00:00:51.340
and music librarian specialist
in the Hispanic division.

00:00:51.340 --> 00:00:56.320 position:56%
Miguel Zenon was born and raised on
the beautiful island of Puerto Rico,

00:00:56.320 --> 00:00:59.020
where he attended Le
Universidad es Musica.

00:00:59.020 --> 00:01:02.790
He received his bachelor's degree
in jazz studies at Berkeley College

00:01:02.790 --> 00:01:05.260
of Music and a master's
degree in jazz performance

00:01:05.260 --> 00:01:06.820
from the Manhattan School of Music.

00:01:06.820 --> 00:01:11.610 position:56%
But as we know, musicians test their
chops collaborating with others.

00:01:11.610 --> 00:01:14.800
And the list of musicians
Miguel has collaborated

00:01:14.800 --> 00:01:16.360
with is quite impressive.

00:01:16.360 --> 00:01:20.240
I will not name them all of course,
but they include Charlie Hayden,

00:01:20.240 --> 00:01:25.320
David Sanchez, Gear McKlein, the
Jeff Ballard Trio, Steve Coleman

00:01:25.320 --> 00:01:29.260
and Dominguez Band
among many others.

00:01:29.260 --> 00:01:32.750
He has been a [inaudible]
in nearly 80 recordings.

00:01:32.750 --> 00:01:35.000
15 of those recordings have been

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:38.050
with the award-winning
band SF Jazz Collective,

00:01:38.050 --> 00:01:41.970
of which Miguel is one
of the founding members.

00:01:41.970 --> 00:01:46.030
Miguel has also led his
own quartet for 15 years

00:01:46.030 --> 00:01:51.420
and has recorded ten albums, all
received with the highest praise

00:01:51.420 --> 00:01:55.660
by the press and the public,
starting with Looking Forward

00:01:55.660 --> 00:01:58.830
in 2002, selected by
the New York Times

00:01:58.830 --> 00:02:02.270
as the number one alternative
jazz album of the year.

00:02:02.270 --> 00:02:07.380
His latest album, Typical, was
released this year in February.

00:02:07.380 --> 00:02:11.520
I want to highlight just a couple
of things from Miguel's outstanding

00:02:11.520 --> 00:02:14.940
and impressive career
at such a young age.

00:02:14.940 --> 00:02:19.280
And we'll get to talk about
many others in our conversation.

00:02:19.280 --> 00:02:21.120
Miguel is the recipient
of a fellowship

00:02:21.120 --> 00:02:23.410
from the John Simon
Guggenheim Foundation

00:02:23.410 --> 00:02:27.290
which supported the recording
of Esta Blena, hailed by critics

00:02:27.290 --> 00:02:32.000
in the US and Puerto Rico as one
of the best recordings of 2009.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:34.050
It also received two
Grammy nominations,

00:02:34.050 --> 00:02:37.910 position:56%
one for best improvised solo and one
for best jazz recording of the year,

00:02:37.910 --> 00:02:39.560 position:56%
as well as a Latin Grammy nomination

00:02:39.560 --> 00:02:42.510
for best Latin jazz
recording of the year.

00:02:42.510 --> 00:02:46.630
Miguel was again nominated
for a Grammy award in 2012

00:02:46.630 --> 00:02:49.160
for best large jazz ensemble album.

00:02:49.160 --> 00:02:52.510
And another Latin Grammy award
for best instrumental album

00:02:52.510 --> 00:02:57.710
for Alma Alventro, the Puerto
Rican Songbook, which pays tribute

00:02:57.710 --> 00:03:01.660
to the compositions and
explorers of music of some

00:03:01.660 --> 00:03:07.500 position:56%
of the great Puerto Rican composers,
[inaudible], Pedro Flores,

00:03:07.500 --> 00:03:09.600
Rafael Hernandez and
Silvia [inaudible].

00:03:09.600 --> 00:03:13.500
And is my personal favorite album.

00:03:13.500 --> 00:03:16.170
His ninth album, Identities
are Changeable,

00:03:16.170 --> 00:03:20.000
also received a Grammy award
nomination in 2014 and was hailed

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:23.560
by critics as one of the best
jazz recordings of the year.

00:03:23.560 --> 00:03:26.340
Besides being an accomplished
musician and composer,

00:03:26.340 --> 00:03:30.320
Miguel is also an educator and
is a permanent faculty member

00:03:30.320 --> 00:03:33.200
of the New England
Conservatory of Music.

00:03:33.200 --> 00:03:35.640
He has also taught and led
workshops around the world,

00:03:35.640 --> 00:03:38.200
including the Bounce Center,
[inaudible], the Conservatory

00:03:38.200 --> 00:03:42.830
of Paris, among many others.

00:03:42.830 --> 00:03:46.450
In 2003 he was chosen by the
Kennedy Center to teach and perform

00:03:46.450 --> 00:03:50.000
in West Africa as part of
their jazz ambassadors program.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:52.960
And since 2011 he has led
the program [Spanish name]

00:03:52.960 --> 00:03:57.480
in Puerto Rico and will be
talking about that briefly.

00:03:57.480 --> 00:04:01.580
In 2008, Miguel received the
prestigious MacArthur Fellowship,

00:04:01.580 --> 00:04:05.260
also known as the Genius
Grant, for --

00:04:05.260 --> 00:04:08.720
and I quote from the
Fellowship's page --

00:04:08.720 --> 00:04:12.300
"For expanding the boundaries
of Latin and jazz music

00:04:12.300 --> 00:04:16.830
through his elegant and
innovative musical collages.

00:04:16.830 --> 00:04:19.930
In his work as a saxophonist
and a composer,

00:04:19.930 --> 00:04:26.230 position:56%
Zenon demonstrates an astonishing
mastery of old and new jazz mediums,

00:04:26.230 --> 00:04:30.000
from African American and Latin
American rhythmic concepts

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:32.220
to free avant garde jazz."

00:04:32.220 --> 00:04:34.170
Miguel, welcome to the
Library of Congress

00:04:34.170 --> 00:04:35.520
and thank you for being here.

00:04:35.520 --> 00:04:36.820
&gt;&gt; Miguel Zenon: Thank you.

00:04:36.820 --> 00:04:38.120
It's great to be here, Talia.

00:04:38.120 --> 00:04:39.920
Thank you.

00:04:39.920 --> 00:04:48.010
[ Applause ]

00:04:48.010 --> 00:04:49.310
&gt;&gt; Talia Guzman-Gonzalez:

00:04:49.310 --> 00:04:50.610
For today's event I will be
asking Miguel a couple questions,

00:04:50.610 --> 00:04:53.980
and my colleague Larry
will be asking some others.

00:04:53.980 --> 00:04:57.470
We'll have an opportunity of Q
and A and there's a special treat

00:04:57.470 --> 00:04:59.220
of Miguel playing for
us today as well.

00:04:59.220 --> 00:05:02.850
So we're in for a good time.

00:05:02.850 --> 00:05:06.760
So recently, Kevin Whitehead
reviewed Typical on Fresh Air,

00:05:06.760 --> 00:05:10.530
and he introduced you
with the following words.

00:05:10.530 --> 00:05:14.770
He said, "There are lots of sides
to Zenon's music that only begin

00:05:14.770 --> 00:05:16.850
with a complex insider/outside
status

00:05:16.850 --> 00:05:20.330
of the Puerto Rican jazz musician."

00:05:20.330 --> 00:05:24.180
So I would like to know what
drew you to sax as an instrument?

00:05:24.180 --> 00:05:28.860
And considering the music landscape
in Puerto Rico in the 1980's

00:05:28.860 --> 00:05:34.560
and 1990's, what drew
you to jazz specifically?

00:05:34.560 --> 00:05:38.400
&gt;&gt; Miguel Zenon: Well like you
mentioned, I went to [Spanish name]

00:05:38.400 --> 00:05:41.530
which is a performing arts
middle school and high school

00:05:41.530 --> 00:05:45.780
in the capital of Puerto Rico.

00:05:45.780 --> 00:05:48.450
I went there for six years.

00:05:48.450 --> 00:05:56.130
And when I first started
studying there, I kind of went

00:05:56.130 --> 00:06:08.890
in with the idea that I just wanted
to play an instrument, you know.

00:06:08.890 --> 00:06:12.860
I didn't really have a
particular instrument in mind.

00:06:12.860 --> 00:06:18.740
For some reason I was
attracted to the piano.

00:06:18.740 --> 00:06:24.960
When I got there I was
about 11 years old.

00:06:24.960 --> 00:06:29.400
But when I got there the first
day and you were involved

00:06:29.400 --> 00:06:38.960
on your instrument, everybody got
the same idea as I did of course.

00:06:38.960 --> 00:06:43.420 position:56%
And all the piano spaces were taken.

00:06:43.420 --> 00:06:52.780
So I had to choose something
else and I think the options were

00:06:52.780 --> 00:06:56.530
like oboe, bassoon,
guitar and saxophone.

00:06:56.530 --> 00:07:00.470
And I think there was
someone in my family

00:07:00.470 --> 00:07:02.850
who had a saxophone lying around.

00:07:02.850 --> 00:07:07.040
It just kind of made sense
out of all those instruments.

00:07:07.040 --> 00:07:10.820
I was like, "Yeah, it
kind of makes sense.

00:07:10.820 --> 00:07:12.120
Maybe saxophone."

00:07:12.120 --> 00:07:19.640
And of course it eventually
grew on me.

00:07:19.640 --> 00:07:26.390
But at first I was more attracted
to the idea of being able

00:07:26.390 --> 00:07:30.300
to play any instrument, not really
an instrument in particular.

00:07:30.300 --> 00:07:35.780
I was just attracted
to music in general.

00:07:35.780 --> 00:07:39.790
And I went to that
school for six years.

00:07:39.790 --> 00:07:41.380
It was all classical training,

00:07:41.380 --> 00:07:46.860
so there was no jazz at
the school obviously.

00:07:46.860 --> 00:07:53.430
I was exposed to a lot of
popular music and dance music.

00:07:53.430 --> 00:07:55.900
And some of my early experience

00:07:55.900 --> 00:08:02.650
as a professional musician
was when I was about 14, 15.

00:08:02.650 --> 00:08:07.930
We were playing salsa music,
you know, dance music.

00:08:07.930 --> 00:08:15.770
So that was kind of my early
introduction to playing something

00:08:15.770 --> 00:08:19.760
that wasn't like chamber music.

00:08:19.760 --> 00:08:25.560
And then eventually
towards the end of my period

00:08:25.560 --> 00:08:31.840
of school I discovered jazz through
friends in the school passing

00:08:31.840 --> 00:08:38.080
around tapes and talking about you
know, so and so and Charlie Parker.

00:08:38.080 --> 00:08:41.170
It could be a Latin
American musician

00:08:41.170 --> 00:08:44.770
like Pachito Rivera
or someone like that.

00:08:44.770 --> 00:08:49.790
And I was really curious about the
idea of improvisation at the time,

00:08:49.790 --> 00:08:55.350
because I had never been
exposed to anything like that,

00:08:55.350 --> 00:08:59.260
or had any formal kind of training.

00:08:59.260 --> 00:09:03.070
But I was really curious about it.

00:09:03.070 --> 00:09:08.940
What did it for me at the time
was hearing Charlie parker play.

00:09:08.940 --> 00:09:14.670
The first time I heard
him I was blown away,

00:09:14.670 --> 00:09:22.870 position:56%
not only because he played the same
instrument I played and he played it

00:09:22.870 --> 00:09:29.380
with such an amazing facility
and great technical ability

00:09:29.380 --> 00:09:32.250
and dexterity, et cetera.

00:09:32.250 --> 00:09:36.500
But when I realized that he was
improvising, I was blown away.

00:09:36.500 --> 00:09:39.390
Because I was like,
"How can you do that

00:09:39.390 --> 00:09:41.740
and still play the
instrument that way?"

00:09:41.740 --> 00:09:44.550
You know, such an amazing facility.

00:09:44.550 --> 00:09:47.660
So I kind of became in a good
way obsessed about trying

00:09:47.660 --> 00:09:49.630
to understand what these
musicians were doing.

00:09:49.630 --> 00:09:51.250 position:56%
Discovery jazz music changed my life

00:09:51.250 --> 00:09:52.960
because even though I had been
studying music for a certain amount

00:09:52.960 --> 00:09:54.580
of years at the school, I was
never like really serious about it.

00:09:54.580 --> 00:09:56.380 position:56%
You know, I never really considered
the possibility of being a musician.

00:09:56.380 --> 00:09:57.680
You know, I was interested
in other things.

00:09:57.680 --> 00:09:58.980
I was attracted to the natural
sciences and other things.

00:09:58.980 --> 00:10:00.280
I was probably going to
follow that road somehow.

00:10:00.280 --> 00:10:01.900 position:56%
But discovering jazz, it really made
me passionate about music, you know?

00:10:01.900 --> 00:10:03.430
And I had something I wanted
to understand and discover.

00:10:03.430 --> 00:10:05.050
And from that point on, you know,
it just became a goal of mine

00:10:05.050 --> 00:10:06.790
and I just kind of embarked on that
trip, you know, ever since then.

00:10:06.790 --> 00:10:08.090
&gt;&gt; Talia Guzman-Gonzalez: I'm
sure you would have been a great

00:10:08.090 --> 00:10:09.390
scientist, but I'm
glad you chose the sax.

00:10:09.390 --> 00:10:10.690 position:56%
Puerto Rican culture plays a central
role in your compositions, right?

00:10:10.690 --> 00:10:12.130 position:56%
And in a way it is an archive of our
musical traditions, [Spanish name].

00:10:12.130 --> 00:10:13.720
And at the same time it's a
laboratory where you experiment

00:10:13.720 --> 00:10:15.370
with combinations of sounds and
rhythms to create something new.

00:10:15.370 --> 00:10:17.170
What compelled you to develop this
concept in your own compositions?

00:10:17.170 --> 00:10:18.470
&gt;&gt; Miguel Zenon: Yes,

00:10:18.470 --> 00:10:19.770
so that process was also
something that came later.

00:10:19.770 --> 00:10:21.070
I mean, after I got really
interested in jazz and I realized

00:10:21.070 --> 00:10:22.370
that jazz at least at that
time was not something

00:10:22.370 --> 00:10:23.670
that I could pursue in Puerto Rico.

00:10:23.670 --> 00:10:24.970
There were no higher education
institutions at the time

00:10:24.970 --> 00:10:26.270
where I could study jazz.

00:10:26.270 --> 00:10:27.570
So I had to go somewhere else.

00:10:27.570 --> 00:10:28.870
And Berkeley in Boston
at the time made sense.

00:10:28.870 --> 00:10:30.170
So I ended up going to Berkeley.

00:10:30.170 --> 00:10:31.470
And when I got to Berkeley,
I realized fairly quickly

00:10:31.470 --> 00:10:32.770
that I was lacking a lot in terms
of sort of like the language

00:10:32.770 --> 00:10:34.070
of the jazz style if
you will, you know.

00:10:34.070 --> 00:10:35.370
So I had a lot of work to do.

00:10:35.370 --> 00:10:38.570
And I concentrated on really
trying to play jazz well, you know,

00:10:38.570 --> 00:10:41.210
studying the music, transcribing,
listening, all the things

00:10:41.210 --> 00:10:42.770
that musicians do, you know,

00:10:42.770 --> 00:10:46.060
like immerse yourself
in a style of music.

00:10:46.060 --> 00:10:49.070 position:56%
And I wasn't writing any music and I
wasn't thinking about anything else

00:10:49.070 --> 00:10:52.650
that wasn't jazz music for
about two or three years.

00:10:52.650 --> 00:10:56.450
About the time that I graduated
Berkeley I started writing a little

00:10:56.450 --> 00:11:00.620
music and kind of started to think
about what it was that I wanted,

00:11:00.620 --> 00:11:05.210
if I wrote music, what it was
my music would sound like.

00:11:05.210 --> 00:11:11.020
I realized that all this
effort that I had put in it

00:11:11.020 --> 00:11:14.580
to study jazz music
was not something

00:11:14.580 --> 00:11:16.840
that I had done with
Puerto Rican music.

00:11:16.840 --> 00:11:20.350
I realized that I knew jazz music
better than Puerto Rican music

00:11:20.350 --> 00:11:25.070
because I had studied the
history in a more systematic way.

00:11:25.070 --> 00:11:29.850
You know, I grew up in Puerto Rico,
so I knew the sound of the music,

00:11:29.850 --> 00:11:32.880
but I couldn't explain it to
somebody else if they asked me.

00:11:32.880 --> 00:11:36.130
So I decided that I wanted
to be able to do that,

00:11:36.130 --> 00:11:41.360
and I sort of like again just
went into this kind of like --

00:11:41.360 --> 00:11:43.610
treating it almost like
a research project.

00:11:43.610 --> 00:11:45.490
Saying, "Okay, what is
this style of music?

00:11:45.490 --> 00:11:46.790
Where did it come from?

00:11:46.790 --> 00:11:48.090
What is it's history?

00:11:48.090 --> 00:11:50.210
Different dimensions,
how deep is the family?

00:11:50.210 --> 00:11:51.650
Et cetera, et cetera."

00:11:51.650 --> 00:11:58.920
And as I would go into this style
of music or elements of culture

00:11:58.920 --> 00:12:01.990
or folklore, et cetera, a lot

00:12:01.990 --> 00:12:04.910
of those sounds started finding
their way into some of the music

00:12:04.910 --> 00:12:06.210
that I was starting to write.

00:12:06.210 --> 00:12:12.290 position:56%
And as I did it more and more, I
realized that I would get a lot more

00:12:12.290 --> 00:12:18.330
from the research if I just
focused on one theme, you know.

00:12:18.330 --> 00:12:24.400
So you plan your music
or some of the others.

00:12:24.400 --> 00:12:29.680
So a lot of my recording projects
were born out of this interest

00:12:29.680 --> 00:12:33.210
to understand Puerto Rican music

00:12:33.210 --> 00:12:36.460
and Puerto Rico better,
just for my own sake.

00:12:36.460 --> 00:12:39.850
And I also feel that it
just kind of helped me.

00:12:39.850 --> 00:12:42.080
I mean, I've been living
in the United States

00:12:42.080 --> 00:12:45.610
for about 20 something years
now, so it helps me connect

00:12:45.610 --> 00:12:47.870
to Puerto Rico from afar.

00:12:47.870 --> 00:12:54.380 position:56%
It helped me find a connection to my
side of what made me a Puerto Rican

00:12:54.380 --> 00:13:00.250
and connected to my country
that we use in the music.

00:13:00.250 --> 00:13:02.030
&gt;&gt; Talia Guzman-Gonzalez:
That's very interesting

00:13:02.030 --> 00:13:05.780 position:56%
about the connections to the island,
because your recording from 2014,

00:13:05.780 --> 00:13:11.200
Identities are Changeable,
explores precisely those links

00:13:11.200 --> 00:13:14.170
that the diaspora has
with the island

00:13:14.170 --> 00:13:17.280
and how we define what
it is to be Puerto Rican.

00:13:17.280 --> 00:13:20.150 position:56%
Could you share with us how you
approached this project and the role

00:13:20.150 --> 00:13:24.390
that the Puerto Rican communities
in Puerto Rico and the US played?

00:13:24.390 --> 00:13:26.200
And what inspired you?

00:13:26.200 --> 00:13:29.180
How did they inspire
you to create it?

00:13:29.180 --> 00:13:31.180 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Miguel Zenon: Yeah, so Identities
are Changeable was a project

00:13:31.180 --> 00:13:37.480
that was born out of again
just curiosity or me trying

00:13:37.480 --> 00:13:41.110
to understand a side of what
it means to be Puerto Rican.

00:13:41.110 --> 00:13:44.520
And like I said, I've been living
in the States for a long time,

00:13:44.520 --> 00:13:47.500
mostly in the New York City area.

00:13:47.500 --> 00:13:50.770
I have family in New York, like
many of us Puerto Ricans do.

00:13:50.770 --> 00:13:55.610
And I've experienced sort of
firsthand this idea of second

00:13:55.610 --> 00:14:00.100
and third generation Puerto
Ricans outside of Puerto Rico.

00:14:00.100 --> 00:14:09.030 position:56%
And this kind of role that exists,
you know, with Puerto Ricans outside

00:14:09.030 --> 00:14:10.720
of Puerto Rico, et cetera.

00:14:10.720 --> 00:14:15.350
So I was really curious about
what this experience was like,

00:14:15.350 --> 00:14:18.080
because this experience was
not my experience, you know.

00:14:18.080 --> 00:14:20.120
And I wanted to understand
it better.

00:14:20.120 --> 00:14:26.060
So what I decided to do was --
this all came out of an initiative,

00:14:26.060 --> 00:14:30.050
a commission from Walker University
when they first approached me.

00:14:30.050 --> 00:14:32.810
Okay, so now I can do this thing.

00:14:32.810 --> 00:14:40.260
And what I decided to do was
interview a series of individuals,

00:14:40.260 --> 00:14:46.520
all second or third generation
Puerto Ricans born and raised in

00:14:46.520 --> 00:14:48.190
or around the New York City area.

00:14:48.190 --> 00:14:51.170
That was kind of my first step.

00:14:51.170 --> 00:14:56.840
I just wanted to talk to them about
their experience, about you know,

00:14:56.840 --> 00:14:59.700
how they felt as Puerto
Ricans or New Yorkers or both,

00:14:59.700 --> 00:15:02.250
and their identity in general.

00:15:02.250 --> 00:15:07.590 position:56%
And as I went through the interviews
and the questions of getting people

00:15:07.590 --> 00:15:11.010
to join the project, I started
