together these concerts.

00:19:34.350 --> 00:19:35.650
What we do is pretty simple.

00:19:35.650 --> 00:19:36.950
We put together a free of charge
jazz concert in the rural areas

00:19:36.950 --> 00:19:38.250
of Puerto Rico, so everything
outside of the metropolitan areas

00:19:38.250 --> 00:19:39.550
of San Juan and surrounding areas.

00:19:39.550 --> 00:19:40.850
And each concert is focused on a
specific historical jazz figure,

00:19:40.850 --> 00:19:42.340
be it Miles Davis, John Coltrane,
Charles Parker, et cetera.

00:19:42.340 --> 00:19:43.810
I mean, the locations of course,
we've been all over the place.

00:19:43.810 --> 00:19:45.110
We've been to [inaudible]
and some of those places too.

00:19:45.110 --> 00:19:46.410
And they vary from theater to
school theaters to you know --

00:19:46.410 --> 00:19:47.920
I think we did one at the Lion's
Club with everybody, you know.

00:19:47.920 --> 00:19:49.220
But that's a part of the idea.

00:19:49.220 --> 00:19:50.520
We use what the community
has at its disposal

00:19:50.520 --> 00:19:51.820
and we have [inaudible]
and people come out.

00:19:51.820 --> 00:19:53.120
So it's a mixed crowd, you know,

00:19:53.120 --> 00:19:54.420
from kids to older
people and families.

00:19:54.420 --> 00:19:55.720
It's been great.

00:19:55.720 --> 00:19:57.020
So a part of the thing we do
is we put together the concert.

00:19:57.020 --> 00:19:58.320
Before the concert we'll do a
pre-concert talk where we talk

00:19:58.320 --> 00:19:59.620
about the history of jazz.

00:19:59.620 --> 00:20:00.920
We talk about sort of the basic
concepts of improvisation.

00:20:00.920 --> 00:20:02.220
So we give people sort
of like a perspective

00:20:02.220 --> 00:20:03.520
of what they're about to hear.

00:20:03.520 --> 00:20:04.820
Because most of the people, I would
say of all the concerts we do,

00:20:04.820 --> 00:20:06.120
about 75% of the public have never
been to a jazz concert before.

00:20:06.120 --> 00:20:07.420
So we try to give them
a little perspective.

00:20:07.420 --> 00:20:08.720
We talk about the music of a chosen
composer, you know, be it Miles

00:20:08.720 --> 00:20:10.020
or -- we talk about their
life, their history, et cetera.

00:20:10.020 --> 00:20:11.320
And then we do the concert and
we always finish the concert

00:20:11.320 --> 00:20:12.620
by incorporating a group of
young students from the community

00:20:12.620 --> 00:20:13.920
and that's always of course
the climax of the thing.

00:20:13.920 --> 00:20:17.530
Because not only you get
to kind of like pass this

00:20:17.530 --> 00:20:24.520
on to a younger generation of
young musicians who are interested

00:20:24.520 --> 00:20:28.450
in getting out there, but also
I feel that it's important

00:20:28.450 --> 00:20:32.150
that these communities feel that
they're part of the project.

00:20:32.150 --> 00:20:34.740
That it's not just us coming
in and playing and leaving,

00:20:34.740 --> 00:20:37.410
but they're adding something to it.

00:20:37.410 --> 00:20:43.160
And just a couple years ago
we started giving out little

00:20:43.160 --> 00:20:45.320
like scholarships, like
a little grant to one

00:20:45.320 --> 00:20:47.350
of the students that plays.

00:20:47.350 --> 00:20:50.310
So we give them a little money
so they can buy instruments

00:20:50.310 --> 00:20:52.340
or take lessons and et cetera.

00:20:52.340 --> 00:20:59.790
And I think we've had
maybe 11 or 12 concerts.

00:20:59.790 --> 00:21:01.090
I can't remember.

00:21:01.090 --> 00:21:04.940
But I would definitely say
that this has been the most --

00:21:04.940 --> 00:21:07.940
at least to me -- the
most rewarding experience

00:21:07.940 --> 00:21:10.010
that I've been in with music.

00:21:10.010 --> 00:21:13.680
You know, this idea of just
putting these concerts together,

00:21:13.680 --> 00:21:15.530
not thinking about ticket sales,

00:21:15.530 --> 00:21:17.240
not thinking about
publicity or anything.

00:21:17.240 --> 00:21:18.540
