00:30:36.890 --> 00:30:39.450
or any creative musician,
what are you listening for?

00:30:39.450 --> 00:30:43.230
&gt;&gt; Miguel Zenon: Well,
that's a good question.

00:30:43.230 --> 00:30:50.960
You know, as an instrumentalist
and someone that spends a lot

00:30:50.960 --> 00:30:54.070
of time playing an instrument,
it's hard for me to disconnect

00:30:54.070 --> 00:30:56.770
from listening to music from
that perspective, you know?

00:30:56.770 --> 00:30:58.940
So usually if I hear
someone playing,

00:30:58.940 --> 00:31:02.380
especially if they're playing
jazz, if they're playing any music,

00:31:02.380 --> 00:31:06.720
I'm pretty much hearing chords and
notes and rhythm you know, first.

00:31:06.720 --> 00:31:08.270
That's usually the
first thing I hear.

00:31:08.270 --> 00:31:11.070
What keys it's on,
what notes are playing,

00:31:11.070 --> 00:31:12.370
what's the beat, what's the feel.

00:31:12.370 --> 00:31:15.730
You know, that kind of stuff.

00:31:15.730 --> 00:31:21.000
But the music that I find
usually attractive in terms

00:31:21.000 --> 00:31:26.990 position:56%
of if I'm listening to an improviser
for example, or someone that's kind

00:31:26.990 --> 00:31:34.330
of from a jazz perspective, I'm
attracted to personality in sound.

00:31:34.330 --> 00:31:39.150
And that's something
that I work on myself.

00:31:39.150 --> 00:31:44.050
And I've always been really
interested on this idea

00:31:44.050 --> 00:31:48.260
that the instrument is a
reflection of our personality

00:31:48.260 --> 00:31:51.600
and it's a reflection of
the way our bodies move.

00:31:51.600 --> 00:31:55.320
And because I'm an instrumentalist
I know how hard it is to attain

00:31:55.320 --> 00:31:57.580
and get to a point where
you get that instrument

00:31:57.580 --> 00:31:59.440
to really be an extension of you.

00:31:59.440 --> 00:32:04.820
So when I hear Charlie Parker
or [inaudible] musicians

00:32:04.820 --> 00:32:08.590
in that category and I hear
the personality in their sound,

00:32:08.590 --> 00:32:11.770
that's the first thing
that brings me

00:32:11.770 --> 00:32:19.280
in before what they actually
are playing, you know.

00:32:19.280 --> 00:32:28.330
And then, again I'm really
just saying this specifically

00:32:28.330 --> 00:32:29.990
about jazz music.

00:32:29.990 --> 00:32:35.010
I'm listening to a
connection to the evolution

00:32:35.010 --> 00:32:39.730
of the tradition of jazz, you know.

00:32:39.730 --> 00:32:43.200
What connection do they have to
the evolution of the language.

00:32:43.200 --> 00:32:47.050
And again, I think I might
have mentioned this before,

00:32:47.050 --> 00:32:48.460 position:56%
but when I think about jazz music --

00:32:48.460 --> 00:32:52.460
when I first started getting into
music I realized fairly quickly

00:32:52.460 --> 00:32:55.070
that this was a language
first of all.

00:32:55.070 --> 00:32:57.480
And second that it
wasn't my language.

00:32:57.480 --> 00:33:00.900
So I had to kind of learn it
from scratch, much like learning

00:33:00.900 --> 00:33:03.120 position:56%
to speak English in a way, you know?

00:33:03.120 --> 00:33:08.010
So when I hear players, be it
older or more modern players,

00:33:08.010 --> 00:33:10.530
I'm listening for that connection.

00:33:10.530 --> 00:33:18.240 position:56%
And it's easier for me to relate to
someone that has a deeper connection

00:33:18.240 --> 00:33:26.010
or something that I can hear more
clearly than someone that doesn't.

00:33:26.010 --> 00:33:27.560
You know, so if I hear
that connection,

00:33:27.560 --> 00:33:32.410
in some way it's easier
for me to relate.

00:33:32.410 --> 00:33:33.910
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: So
language is one thing.

00:33:33.910 --> 00:33:40.320 position:56%
I want to ask you about sound,
specifically your sound on the horn.

00:33:40.320 --> 00:33:46.060
When we learn to speak, we're not
necessarily conscious of the sound

00:33:46.060 --> 00:33:48.890
of our voice, the spoken voice.

00:33:48.890 --> 00:33:54.520
But I wonder, how conscious
is your sound on your horn?

00:33:54.520 --> 00:33:56.460
&gt;&gt; Miguel Zenon: Well, I
like to think about this

00:33:56.460 --> 00:33:59.810
in sort of like two ways.

00:33:59.810 --> 00:34:04.910
One way is the personality
thing that I mentioned before,

00:34:04.910 --> 00:34:09.930 position:56%
where we're really trying to portray
something that's unique to us.

00:34:09.930 --> 00:34:13.560
And it's like it might be
inspired by someone you admire,

00:34:13.560 --> 00:34:20.490
like in my case Charlie Parker and
Coltrane or somebody that I like.

00:34:20.490 --> 00:34:24.520 position:56%
And probably my sound is going to
be some kind of combination of that,

00:34:24.520 --> 00:34:28.660
or try to be a combination of that
and other things that I like too.

00:34:28.660 --> 00:34:30.470
So that's one side of it.

00:34:30.470 --> 00:34:35.430
But in my opinion that's sort
of like the easier side of it.

00:34:35.430 --> 00:34:39.590
The harder part is really
being able to connect

00:34:39.590 --> 00:34:41.480
to the instrument physically.

00:34:41.480 --> 00:34:45.450
And as an instrumentalist, a lot
of the things that we do and most

00:34:45.450 --> 00:34:48.580
of the time that we spend
on the instrument is trying

00:34:48.580 --> 00:34:54.220
to make this connection as
natural and seamless as possible.

00:34:54.220 --> 00:34:58.580
That takes a lot of time of course.

00:34:58.580 --> 00:35:02.620
And at least myself, I don't feel
that when I pick up the instrument,

00:35:02.620 --> 00:35:05.220
the saxophone, it's not something

00:35:05.220 --> 00:35:10.960
that my body is naturally
instructed to do.

00:35:10.960 --> 00:35:13.010
You know, I have to
train myself to be able

00:35:13.010 --> 00:35:16.740
to actually produce a
sound and a quality sound.

00:35:16.740 --> 00:35:21.030
So I have to use parts of my
body when I play the saxophone

00:35:21.030 --> 00:35:23.510 position:56%
and use them in a very specific way.

00:35:23.510 --> 00:35:29.940
And I use them in a way that I
don't use doing anything else,

00:35:29.940 --> 00:35:32.190
doing my daily routine.

00:35:32.190 --> 00:35:34.710
I have to use my diaphragm
in a very specific way,

00:35:34.710 --> 00:35:38.010
use my lungs in a very specific
way, the muscles in my face

00:35:38.010 --> 00:35:40.870
and my oral cavity and my throat.

00:35:40.870 --> 00:35:45.380
That all adds to that
idea of just being able

00:35:45.380 --> 00:35:48.170
to produce a sound, like one note.

00:35:48.170 --> 00:35:55.480 position:56%
So to me it's a balance between this
physical, almost like an athlete,

00:35:55.480 --> 00:36:01.560
fitness kind of thing where you
really need to be fit and in shape

00:36:01.560 --> 00:36:03.700
in order to be able to
produce quality sound.

00:36:03.700 --> 00:36:08.920
And then once you can control
that, then you try to bring

00:36:08.920 --> 00:36:11.190
to that sound personality.

00:36:11.190 --> 00:36:15.970
And like I said, this
could take forever.

00:36:15.970 --> 00:36:17.270
This could take forever.

00:36:17.270 --> 00:36:18.570
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum:
Was there a point

00:36:18.570 --> 00:36:21.990
at which you felt you had
finally arrived at your own sound?

00:36:21.990 --> 00:36:23.840
Your own musical identity?

00:36:23.840 --> 00:36:26.790
&gt;&gt; Miguel Zenon: There was
definitely a point where I felt

00:36:26.790 --> 00:36:29.570
that I was in the right direction,

00:36:29.570 --> 00:36:33.690
that I felt that I had
found something that worked

00:36:33.690 --> 00:36:41.690
and I just kind of needed
to finesse it a little bit.

00:36:41.690 --> 00:36:43.950
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: There's a
mysterious process especially

00:36:43.950 --> 00:36:51.080 position:56%
for jazz players, because so much of
what they do involves improvisation.

00:36:51.080 --> 00:36:55.300
So here's one of my questions, is
how did you learn to improvise?

00:36:55.300 --> 00:36:56.600
&gt;&gt; Miguel Zenon: Okay.

00:36:56.600 --> 00:37:02.240
So one thing about improvisation
that's important to understand --

00:37:02.240 --> 00:37:05.740
and this is something again
that helped me immensely --

00:37:05.740 --> 00:37:08.750
was to understand the
difference between improvisation

00:37:08.750 --> 00:37:12.630
as a general concept and
improvisation within a language

00:37:12.630 --> 00:37:15.150
or within a musical
language in this case.

00:37:15.150 --> 00:37:18.900
Like for example, when I was in
Puerto Rico and I was listening

00:37:18.900 --> 00:37:23.630
and mostly playing salsa music
and listening to that music,

00:37:23.630 --> 00:37:25.750
the language that I
was using to improvise

00:37:25.750 --> 00:37:29.430 position:56%
within that music was very different
than the language I would play

00:37:29.430 --> 00:37:32.240
if I was playing Barbados
or Kangaroo.

00:37:32.240 --> 00:37:34.910
The music is a different language.

00:37:34.910 --> 00:37:37.670
I'm improvising in
both cases, you know,

00:37:37.670 --> 00:37:39.160
but using a different language.

00:37:39.160 --> 00:37:42.380
Again, kind of going back to
this idea of English and Spanish,

00:37:42.380 --> 00:37:45.240
I might be saying the same thing
but using a different language

00:37:45.240 --> 00:37:48.040
and improvising, et cetera.

00:37:48.040 --> 00:37:55.050
So once that became clear to me,
the next step for me was, okay,

00:37:55.050 --> 00:38:01.980
so I want to improvise but I don't
have enough language in this case.

00:38:01.980 --> 00:38:03.840
So I need to acquire more language.

00:38:03.840 --> 00:38:08.070
So I do that by listening, by
transcribing, my immersing myself

00:38:08.070 --> 00:38:10.250
in this language, in this
case in the jazz language.

00:38:10.250 --> 00:38:14.310
And as I get myself more and
more immersed in this language,

00:38:14.310 --> 00:38:16.860
a lot of these things that you
know Charlie Parker played,

00:38:16.860 --> 00:38:20.370
or Corbin Hawk or Alyssa
Young or whoever I like.

00:38:20.370 --> 00:38:26.730
And I check that and I
was influenced by it.

00:38:26.730 --> 00:38:30.730
It starts as something that you
basically repeat, repetition.

00:38:30.730 --> 00:38:32.440
And then it eventually
just becomes second nature.

00:38:32.440 --> 00:38:35.040
You internalize it and
it becomes part of you.

00:38:35.040 --> 00:38:39.380
And the combinations of all
these players eventually becomes

00:38:39.380 --> 00:38:40.860
your personality.

00:38:40.860 --> 00:38:42.330
Along with your own ideas.

00:38:42.330 --> 00:38:45.130 position:56%
I think there's a point where you --

00:38:45.130 --> 00:38:50.240
at least for myself there was
a point where I started to look

00:38:50.240 --> 00:38:53.320
at a Charlie Parker
composition or solo and instead

00:38:53.320 --> 00:38:57.010
of necessarily repeating
what he played,

00:38:57.010 --> 00:38:58.980
I would sort of analyze
what he played.

00:38:58.980 --> 00:39:02.590
And say, "Okay, so if he did
this this way on this chorus

00:39:02.590 --> 00:39:05.850 position:56%
with this rhythm and these notes,
that means that I can turn it around

00:39:05.850 --> 00:39:09.200
and do it differently, or
take a couple more steps."

00:39:09.200 --> 00:39:12.380
And you start building
your language on the idea

00:39:12.380 --> 00:39:15.270
of addition and assimilation.

00:39:15.270 --> 00:39:18.020
And then eventually you use
that language to improvise.

00:39:18.020 --> 00:39:24.840
So I see it more as
improvisation is not necessarily --

00:39:24.840 --> 00:39:28.760
in this case jazz improvisation
is not where you just go up

00:39:28.760 --> 00:39:32.090
and play whatever comes
to your mind.

00:39:32.090 --> 00:39:34.870
But it's sort of like an
organized improvisation.

00:39:34.870 --> 00:39:39.580 position:56%
You're improvising on ideas based on
information that you've already got.

00:39:39.580 --> 00:39:44.090
And you're using that
information to improvise.

00:39:44.090 --> 00:39:47.740
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: I can hear that
you are a somewhat analytic person.

00:39:47.740 --> 00:39:51.870
Are you self-critical?

00:39:51.870 --> 00:39:53.170
&gt;&gt; Miguel Zenon: Yeah.

00:39:53.170 --> 00:39:55.630
Yeah, you could say that too.

00:39:55.630 --> 00:39:56.930
[Laughs].

00:39:56.930 --> 00:39:59.990
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: So when you're
listening to your own music,

00:39:59.990 --> 00:40:05.970 position:56%
or really for any kind of music,
what do you think makes a good solo?

00:40:08.040 --> 00:40:13.670
&gt;&gt; Miguel Zenon: Well, I
think it's a little different

00:40:13.670 --> 00:40:17.540
when I'm listening to myself and
when I'm listening to someone else,

00:40:17.540 --> 00:40:20.590
especially if it's
somebody that I admire.

00:40:20.590 --> 00:40:25.130
Someone like [inaudible]
and Coltrane and all those.

00:40:25.130 --> 00:40:31.380
You know, a lot of those solos,
I listen to them differently

00:40:31.380 --> 00:40:36.450
because they forge
something like what I play.

00:40:36.450 --> 00:40:38.900
So it's harder for
me to be critical.

00:40:38.900 --> 00:40:45.430
But with myself, and
a lot of my friends

00:40:45.430 --> 00:40:47.770
and me do this all the time --

00:40:47.770 --> 00:40:50.690
where I record a concert
and I go listen back.

00:40:50.690 --> 00:40:55.500
And I say, "Okay, maybe this works
and that doesn't work, you know,

00:40:55.500 --> 00:40:57.680
from a perspective of performance."

00:40:57.680 --> 00:41:01.710
It's also perspective of just
like a player, or you know,

00:41:01.710 --> 00:41:05.540
when I'm naturally
playing and improvising.

00:41:05.540 --> 00:41:16.230 position:56%
And I'm listening for things as
basic as time, you know, intonation,

00:41:16.230 --> 00:41:20.960
sound, to interaction
with other musician.

00:41:20.960 --> 00:41:24.520
You know, am I reacting to what's
around me, or am I just kind

00:41:24.520 --> 00:41:30.030
of going blindly and on
my own kind of space?

00:41:30.030 --> 00:41:36.330
And I'm also trying to find when
I listen back to it at least,

00:41:36.330 --> 00:41:39.140
I'm trying to find like a
connecting sort of thread

00:41:39.140 --> 00:41:40.930
through the improvised solo.

00:41:40.930 --> 00:41:46.990
And I'm trying to find
something that --

00:41:46.990 --> 00:41:49.130
you know, you hear this all
the time, tells the story.

00:41:49.130 --> 00:41:52.900
It's kind of that, but it's more --

00:41:52.900 --> 00:41:57.200
I like to think about it
more from the perspective of,

00:41:57.200 --> 00:41:59.540
am I paying enough attention
not only to what's around me,

00:41:59.540 --> 00:42:02.330
but am I paying enough
attention to what I'm playing

00:42:02.330 --> 00:42:04.970
so that I'm not just
sort of rambling

00:42:04.970 --> 00:42:07.730
and I can actually use the
ideas I'm putting out there

00:42:07.730 --> 00:42:11.590
to build something
that's logical and basic?

00:42:11.590 --> 00:42:13.430
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: You teach also.

00:42:13.430 --> 00:42:17.170
Can you teach someone to swing?

00:42:17.170 --> 00:42:18.640
&gt;&gt; Miguel Zenon: I think so.

00:42:18.640 --> 00:42:21.780
I mean, it's not going
to be the kind of thing

00:42:21.780 --> 00:42:23.370
where it's going to
take five minutes.

00:42:23.370 --> 00:42:25.040
But I think you can do it.

00:42:25.040 --> 00:42:26.340
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum:
How would you do it?

00:42:26.340 --> 00:42:27.710
&gt;&gt; Miguel Zenon: I think
it's like anything.

00:42:27.710 --> 00:42:34.450
I think that kind of
thing has to do with --

00:42:34.450 --> 00:42:39.930 position:56%
it's almost like learning an accent,
like if you're speaking a language

00:42:39.930 --> 00:42:41.230
and learning an accent, you know.

00:42:41.230 --> 00:42:42.770
Like I was somewhere the other day

00:42:42.770 --> 00:42:46.820 position:56%
and someone told me I had a New York
accent and I was blown away by that.

00:42:46.820 --> 00:42:48.120
I was like, "Really?

00:42:48.120 --> 00:42:49.420
A New York accent?

00:42:49.420 --> 00:42:51.040
I've never even thought
about that before."

00:42:51.040 --> 00:42:53.210
But it's almost like if
you're teaching someone

00:42:53.210 --> 00:42:55.900
to learn a British accent
or something like that.

00:42:55.900 --> 00:42:58.130
It kind of is -- the
only way you can do

00:42:58.130 --> 00:43:00.120
that is by immersion, you know.

00:43:00.120 --> 00:43:04.300
By just listening and playing along
and listening and playing along.

00:43:04.300 --> 00:43:07.570
And a lot of times what I end up
saying, when I hear someone play,

00:43:07.570 --> 00:43:11.780
like a drummer or a pianist and
I'm talking about slow swing

00:43:11.780 --> 00:43:16.730
for example, and I will say like
your swing feel is too straight

00:43:16.730 --> 00:43:19.720
or it's too exaggerated and so on.

00:43:19.720 --> 00:43:21.810
Sometimes it's too
much on the other side.

00:43:21.810 --> 00:43:23.280
So I would say something like that.

00:43:23.280 --> 00:43:26.550
So I would say, "Okay, so your
swing feel is too straight.

00:43:26.550 --> 00:43:29.650
So why don't you check out
so and so and so and so,

00:43:29.650 --> 00:43:32.110
who's going to pull
you to the other side?"

00:43:32.110 --> 00:43:34.610
And if it's too much of the other
side, then I'm going to say, "Okay,

00:43:34.610 --> 00:43:37.640
so you should be listening to
this, this, this and this."

00:43:37.640 --> 00:43:41.170
You know, just immersion and
listening and transcription

00:43:41.170 --> 00:43:45.110
and trying to find your
place with what you lay.

00:43:45.110 --> 00:43:51.680
I mean, a lot of what we do as
jazz musicians is trying to prove

00:43:51.680 --> 00:43:54.420
to ourselves in the place
of musicians we admire.

00:43:54.420 --> 00:43:56.450
So we play along with records.

00:43:56.450 --> 00:43:59.760
You know, we play along with
records to try to see if I'm going

00:43:59.760 --> 00:44:02.810
to play a [inaudible]
solo or a Coltrane solo.

00:44:02.810 --> 00:44:05.460
I'm going to put that record on
and I'm going to learn that solo,

00:44:05.460 --> 00:44:08.040
and I'm going to try to phrase
it exactly the same way.

00:44:08.040 --> 00:44:11.760 position:56%
I'm going to try to pull things
through the same exact articulation.

00:44:11.760 --> 00:44:16.550
And in that sense we're not only
getting to the notes and the theory

00:44:16.550 --> 00:44:18.630
of it, but the actual feel.

00:44:18.630 --> 00:44:22.660
So a lot of what we do in
terms of learning and feel,

00:44:22.660 --> 00:44:26.700
be it learning how to swing
in jazz, or just learning how

00:44:26.700 --> 00:44:28.000
to make the music feel good,

00:44:28.000 --> 00:44:34.140
is by emulating what's
out there, you know.

00:44:34.140 --> 00:44:37.590
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: Talia
was mentioning not just your

00:44:37.590 --> 00:44:42.140
accomplishments, but the awards
you've received over the years.

00:44:42.140 --> 00:44:45.720
And I wonder, is recognition
important to you?

00:44:48.460 --> 00:44:53.300
&gt;&gt; Miguel Zenon: Well I like to
think about it from a perspective

00:44:53.300 --> 00:44:57.630
of it's something that's
important in terms

00:44:57.630 --> 00:45:00.640
of opening doors to opportunities.

00:45:00.640 --> 00:45:01.940
I mean,

00:45:01.940 --> 00:45:04.470
I definitely feel like things
like the MacArthur Fellowship

00:45:04.470 --> 00:45:08.170
and the Guggenheim
Fellowship, Grammy nominations,

00:45:08.170 --> 00:45:13.980
all those things, they give myself
and my music more visibility

00:45:13.980 --> 00:45:16.060
and opens doors professionally.

00:45:16.060 --> 00:45:20.390
Which makes me work more
and makes my life easier.

00:45:20.390 --> 00:45:28.360 position:56%
But on the other hand, like you
said, I'm self-critical and I'm sort

00:45:28.360 --> 00:45:33.530
of a firm believer on
being my own judge.

00:45:33.530 --> 00:45:40.620
I believe that I'm the
person that's most capacitive

00:45:40.620 --> 00:45:47.090
to really accurately say what
it is that I'm doing wrong

00:45:47.090 --> 00:45:49.740
and what I'm not doing well.

00:45:49.740 --> 00:45:52.440
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: As a
judge, are you forgiving?

00:45:52.440 --> 00:45:53.740
&gt;&gt; Miguel Zenon: Yeah, sure.

00:45:53.740 --> 00:45:55.040
I mean, it's the kind of thing --

00:45:55.040 --> 00:45:58.370
I'm not going to be
totally flagellating myself

00:45:58.370 --> 00:46:00.130
or anything over a solo.

00:46:00.130 --> 00:46:13.070 position:56%
But I take recognition of these kind
of awards as something that's good.

00:46:13.070 --> 00:46:14.840
But even if it was
something that was negative,

00:46:14.840 --> 00:46:16.970
like even if it was a
review, a negative review

00:46:16.970 --> 00:46:21.920
or a positive review, to me
those things are basically

00:46:21.920 --> 00:46:23.560
at the end of the day opinions.

00:46:23.560 --> 00:46:27.040
And they will have effect, like
this opinion and that opinion.

00:46:27.040 --> 00:46:37.020
But at the end of the day, I'm
working sort of based on the amount

00:46:37.020 --> 00:46:42.190
of effort and the amount of
work that I still need to do.

00:46:42.190 --> 00:46:46.980
I mean, I always feel that there's
always something I can do better.

00:46:46.980 --> 00:46:51.050
And it's probably just the way
it's going to be, and that's kind

00:46:51.050 --> 00:46:53.260
of how I do it with my work.

00:46:53.260 --> 00:46:54.820
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: You
never stop learning.

00:46:54.820 --> 00:46:56.120
&gt;&gt; Miguel Zenon: No.

00:46:56.120 --> 00:46:57.420
That's right.

00:46:57.420 --> 00:46:58.910
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: So you
mentioned Charlie Parker

00:46:58.910 --> 00:47:02.630
and I know how important
his music is to you.

00:47:02.630 --> 00:47:04.260
If he were here with us
today, what would you

00:47:04.260 --> 00:47:06.040
like to ask him or
talk to him about?

00:47:06.040 --> 00:47:09.680
&gt;&gt; Miguel Zenon: I would probably
ask him about what he's practicing.

00:47:09.680 --> 00:47:12.610
It's funny you say that,
because there's this interview

00:47:12.610 --> 00:47:17.200
with Paul Desmond,
who I'm sure you know.

00:47:17.200 --> 00:47:19.340
It blows me away every
time I hear it,

00:47:19.340 --> 00:47:22.670
because Paul Desmond was
a great saxophonist too.

00:47:22.670 --> 00:47:26.720
He was asked about his playing.

00:47:26.720 --> 00:47:30.150
And I'm thinking this is probably
like late-40's, early-'50's

00:47:30.150 --> 00:47:35.210
and this music was so new that
you know, to hear someone play

00:47:35.210 --> 00:47:40.840
that way is almost like someone
inventing a whole new language

00:47:40.840 --> 00:47:46.020
within a period of like two years,
and then that language becoming it,

00:47:46.020 --> 00:47:49.040
like what everybody
wanted to play like.

00:47:49.040 --> 00:47:51.020
And then it was like
the greatest thing.

00:47:51.020 --> 00:47:53.150
And still now I hear
it and I'm like, "Wow,

00:47:53.150 --> 00:47:54.960
this is the greatest thing ever."

00:47:54.960 --> 00:47:58.190
You know, and on the interview
he's talking to Charlie Parker

00:47:58.190 --> 00:48:01.280
about his practice routine.

00:48:01.280 --> 00:48:04.740
And it blew me away what
Charlie Parker was talking about,

00:48:04.740 --> 00:48:06.230
how much he practiced.

00:48:06.230 --> 00:48:11.520
At some point he said, "I might
be practicing 10-11 hours a day."

00:48:11.520 --> 00:48:14.870
But a lot of what he was
practicing were things

00:48:14.870 --> 00:48:16.950
that were really basic things.

00:48:16.950 --> 00:48:20.350
You know, scales, time,
just assimilating solos.

00:48:20.350 --> 00:48:26.360
So I'm always interested
in how you know,

00:48:26.360 --> 00:48:31.540 position:56%
musicians build their routines, you
know, build their routines and build

00:48:31.540 --> 00:48:33.560
on things that are
important to them, you know.

00:48:33.560 --> 00:48:35.060
So I would probably
ask him something

00:48:35.060 --> 00:48:37.420
about his practice routine.

00:48:37.420 --> 00:48:40.770 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: I'm very
curious what your questions will be.

00:48:40.770 --> 00:48:44.800
And you'll have a chance to
ask them in just a moment.

00:48:44.800 --> 00:48:49.650
I'll ask one last one, and that is,
as a musician, composer, arranger,

00:48:49.650 --> 00:48:53.970
educator, as a father, how
do you measure success?

00:48:56.120 --> 00:48:57.420
&gt;&gt; Miguel Zenon: It's hard to say.

00:48:57.420 --> 00:49:00.870
I mean, I think probably
the way I would do it --

00:49:00.870 --> 00:49:03.980
and this is kind of how I
think about this in general.

00:49:03.980 --> 00:49:09.850
When I started playing this music
and when I decided that I wanted

00:49:09.850 --> 00:49:17.270 position:56%
to be a musician for a living, I did
it because my goal was to be able

00:49:17.270 --> 00:49:20.940
to play with people I
admired, you know, my heroes.

00:49:20.940 --> 00:49:26.310
And I've gotten to do that
a bunch over the years

00:49:26.310 --> 00:49:29.620
and I feel you know
very lucky about that.

00:49:29.620 --> 00:49:35.550
I never really thought of music
as a way of creating a platform

00:49:35.550 --> 00:49:38.330
for myself as an individual artist.

00:49:38.330 --> 00:49:41.220
I never thought that
someday I'm going

00:49:41.220 --> 00:49:44.130
to have my own band
and my own records.

00:49:44.130 --> 00:49:48.110 position:56%
I mean, eventually that happened and
it's been a great experience too.

00:49:48.110 --> 00:49:51.730
But I usually measure in terms

00:49:51.730 --> 00:49:56.550
of our very small,
little jazz world here.

00:49:56.550 --> 00:50:01.070 position:56%
I measure musicians sort of in terms
of who they play with, you know.

00:50:01.070 --> 00:50:05.000
And if I see a musician who's
playing with a whole bunch

00:50:05.000 --> 00:50:08.850 position:56%
of different people, I think, "Okay,
so that guy must be good, you know."

00:50:08.850 --> 00:50:15.220
He's respected in the
community and he's first call

00:50:15.220 --> 00:50:16.860
for these different projects.

00:50:16.860 --> 00:50:21.390
So they must have something
that all these musicians

00:50:21.390 --> 00:50:24.160
from different places
are attracted to.

00:50:24.160 --> 00:50:28.420
So I feel that as I get to play
with more musicians and I get

00:50:28.420 --> 00:50:34.190
to be more experienced,
I feel good about that.

00:50:34.190 --> 00:50:37.930
You know, more than anything
else, that I have that kind

00:50:37.930 --> 00:50:40.750
of connection to the community.

00:50:40.750 --> 00:50:42.050
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: That's it.

00:50:42.050 --> 00:50:43.720
You must be good.

00:50:43.720 --> 00:50:46.090
[ Laughter ]

00:50:46.090 --> 00:50:47.900
Okay, again, think
about your questions.

00:50:47.900 --> 00:50:52.750
But you know, I couldn't help but
notice you have your horn with you.

00:50:52.750 --> 00:50:54.430
Yes, right behind the chair.

00:50:54.430 --> 00:50:59.510 position:56%
I wonder if you could be persuaded
to let that bad boy out of the case.

00:50:59.510 --> 00:51:05.110
[ Applause ]

00:51:05.110 --> 00:51:06.410
&gt;&gt; Talia Guzman-Gonzalez:
Questions first?

00:51:06.410 --> 00:51:07.710
&gt;&gt; Miguel Zenon: Maybe we
do the questions first.

00:51:07.710 --> 00:51:09.010
&gt;&gt; AL: Okay.

00:51:09.010 --> 00:51:11.830
Who has a question?

00:51:11.830 --> 00:51:13.620
There's one right there.

00:51:13.620 --> 00:51:17.680
&gt;&gt; I had a question for
all of us amateur musicians

00:51:17.680 --> 00:51:26.170 position:56%
about how you encourage people to be
willing to take the chance to get up

00:51:26.170 --> 00:51:29.050
and play in front of other people.

00:51:29.050 --> 00:51:30.700
&gt;&gt; Miguel Zenon: Well you know,
that takes some courage for sure,

00:51:30.700 --> 00:51:33.030
especially if you're
just getting started

00:51:33.030 --> 00:51:35.720
and if you haven't
had the experience.

00:51:35.720 --> 00:51:40.680
But I feel like it's
like anything, you know?

00:51:40.680 --> 00:51:44.430
As you gain confidence
in what you're doing,

00:51:44.430 --> 00:51:48.560
and that was my experience,
you know, the more I practiced

00:51:48.560 --> 00:51:51.920
and the more I felt that
I could do something

00:51:51.920 --> 00:51:54.340
with a certain amount of comfort.

00:51:54.340 --> 00:51:56.480
It became a little
easier to get up on stage

00:51:56.480 --> 00:51:58.020
and play in front of people.

00:51:58.020 --> 00:52:00.860
Of course, the first time
I did it I was terrified.

00:52:00.860 --> 00:52:05.220
And the second time a little less,
and the third time a little less.

00:52:05.220 --> 00:52:08.210
And it kind of goes like that.

00:52:08.210 --> 00:52:11.080
I've been doing this
for a long time.

00:52:11.080 --> 00:52:17.070
Still, once in a while you know,
I'll get a little something.

00:52:17.070 --> 00:52:21.520
Maybe it's a family member in
the audience or someone I admire,

00:52:21.520 --> 00:52:23.030
so I'm getting really jitterish.

00:52:23.030 --> 00:52:32.520
But after a while if you do it
enough, it just becomes routine.

00:52:32.520 --> 00:52:35.150
It just becomes something
that you're comfortable with.

00:52:35.150 --> 00:52:36.450
&gt;&gt; AL: Who else?

00:52:36.450 --> 00:52:37.750
There is one right there.

00:52:37.750 --> 00:52:39.050 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Thank you so much for being here.

00:52:39.050 --> 00:52:40.350
[Inaudible].

00:52:40.350 --> 00:52:42.150
I first saw you 20 years
ago performing at --

00:52:42.150 --> 00:52:58.040
[ Inaudible ]

00:52:58.040 --> 00:53:00.900
&gt;&gt; Miguel Zenon: So David
and I, we actually went

00:53:00.900 --> 00:53:04.950
to the same performing arts school
in Puerto Rico, the [Spanish name].

00:53:04.950 --> 00:53:08.780
He went there -- he's about
eight years older than I am.

00:53:08.780 --> 00:53:10.100
So he was there way before me

00:53:10.100 --> 00:53:12.230
and I didn't meet him
at the school of course.

00:53:12.230 --> 00:53:14.080
But we went through
the same courses.

00:53:14.080 --> 00:53:17.050
We had the same saxophone
teacher and everything, you know.

00:53:17.050 --> 00:53:22.070
And of course when I was at the
school, when I was finishing up

00:53:22.070 --> 00:53:25.520
and getting into jazz, he was kind
of like putting out first records.

00:53:25.520 --> 00:53:28.140 position:56%
So I was a great admirer of his work

00:53:28.140 --> 00:53:33.020
like when I was just
getting started.

00:53:33.020 --> 00:53:36.990
Eventually once I moved to
Boston I got really close

00:53:36.990 --> 00:53:41.140
with another Latin American
musician, Danilo Perez.

00:53:41.140 --> 00:53:45.460
He was a pianist and composer.

00:53:45.460 --> 00:53:48.450
And Danilo sort of
became a mentor in Boston.

00:53:48.450 --> 00:53:52.070 position:56%
You know, I spent a lot of time with
him and would go off to his house,

00:53:52.070 --> 00:53:54.390 position:56%
take lessons, play with him a bunch.

00:53:54.390 --> 00:53:57.970
So I met David through Danilo
while I was still in Boston.

00:53:57.970 --> 00:54:00.530
I still remember when I met him.

00:54:00.530 --> 00:54:02.530
We met at this place for dinner and
then David was playing that night.

00:54:02.530 --> 00:54:08.110
I came over and I sat in and
played with him and it was cool.

00:54:08.110 --> 00:54:10.750
And then eventually when I
started figuring out what to do

00:54:10.750 --> 00:54:13.860
after school, after Berkeley,
some folks suggested,

00:54:13.860 --> 00:54:15.160
"You should go to New York."

00:54:15.160 --> 00:54:17.420
I thought, "Okay, maybe
I'll try that."

00:54:17.420 --> 00:54:20.690
I had family in New York so
that made sense at the time.

00:54:20.690 --> 00:54:22.120
I was going to school in New York.

00:54:22.120 --> 00:54:23.420
And when I was in New York,

00:54:23.420 --> 00:54:25.070
the first thing I did
was I called up David.

00:54:25.070 --> 00:54:26.660
You know, I was like,
"I'm in New York.

00:54:26.660 --> 00:54:29.180
Remember we met in Boston?"

00:54:29.180 --> 00:54:32.590
And David did basically
exactly the same thing

00:54:32.590 --> 00:54:33.890
that Danilo did, you know.

00:54:33.890 --> 00:54:36.210
I would go over to his house
and he became a mentor.

00:54:36.210 --> 00:54:38.020
I would go over to
his house like, "Man,

00:54:38.020 --> 00:54:39.740
I'm kind of playing on this tune.

00:54:39.740 --> 00:54:41.190 position:56%
Do you think you hear another line?"

00:54:41.190 --> 00:54:42.830
He was like, "Maybe I
hear a counter line."

00:54:42.830 --> 00:54:45.100
And I started doing
that just for fun.

00:54:45.100 --> 00:54:48.080 position:56%
And then it was like, "You know, we
should play that at the gig tonight.

00:54:48.080 --> 00:54:49.380
Why don't you come over?"

00:54:49.380 --> 00:54:50.680
And I went and played.

00:54:50.680 --> 00:54:51.980
And we did that in Boston.

00:54:51.980 --> 00:54:53.280
It was like, "Why don't
you come on tour?"

00:54:53.280 --> 00:54:55.950
I did that and started
playing with him.

00:54:55.950 --> 00:54:59.420
The relationship was born
out of that sort of dynamic.

00:54:59.420 --> 00:55:04.680
And just kind of going back to
this idea of David and Danilo,

00:55:04.680 --> 00:55:08.560 position:56%
they're very close friends and they
both played together for a long time

00:55:08.560 --> 00:55:10.710
with [inaudible] and a
bunch of other bands.

00:55:10.710 --> 00:55:14.720
And to me, when I started
getting into jazz,

00:55:14.720 --> 00:55:17.510
they represented what
I wanted to achieve,

00:55:17.510 --> 00:55:19.150 position:56%
not in terms of success or anything.

00:55:19.150 --> 00:55:26.140 position:56%
But I felt that as working musicians
they have both been able to get

00:55:26.140 --> 00:55:30.310
to a place where they can be
respected as jazz musicians,

00:55:30.310 --> 00:55:33.000
you know, authentic jazz musicians.

00:55:33.000 --> 00:55:37.980
But at the same time,
represent their culture, right?

00:55:37.980 --> 00:55:42.190
In the case of David and Danilo,
they are both very connected

00:55:42.190 --> 00:55:43.690
to you know, the music
of the country and trying

00:55:43.690 --> 00:55:45.260
to represent that in their music.

00:55:45.260 --> 00:55:51.550
And I related to that idea
very deeply, you know.

00:55:51.550 --> 00:55:56.870
And I related to the idea of making
music that wasn't just sound.

00:55:56.870 --> 00:56:02.210
Sort of like instrumental
dance music kind of thing,

00:56:02.210 --> 00:56:06.490
but that had more of a
balance between what I consider

00:56:06.490 --> 00:56:09.950
to be essential elements of
jazz, interaction, you know,

00:56:09.950 --> 00:56:14.630
this idea of taking risk and
letting things kind of flow.

00:56:14.630 --> 00:56:18.530
And combining that with
folklore and all this.

00:56:18.530 --> 00:56:21.900
And I felt the music at the time
represented that, and that was kind

00:56:21.900 --> 00:56:23.990
of what I was trying to achieve.

00:56:23.990 --> 00:56:28.340 position:56%
So it was really nice to cross paths
with them and eventually you know,

00:56:28.340 --> 00:56:31.300
become part of their
little circle in a way.

00:56:31.300 --> 00:56:33.060
So that was really great.

00:56:33.060 --> 00:56:34.360
Thank you.

00:56:34.360 --> 00:56:35.660
